NETWORK CONTROL PROCEDURE
.center 75
SOFTWARE DUMPS
.skip 2
I. Purpose
.skip 1
This procedure defines the process by which a dump may be performed
and the variety of software dumps that are available.
.skip 2
II. Definition
.skip 1
A dump is a mirror image of the code that is running in a node or slot
which is stored online to be examined at a later time.
.skip 2
III. Procedure
.skip 1
When ever a node crashes a dump should be performed. This is accomplished
via the network utility LOADII.
.skip 1
Each dump will have a unique file naming convention which is as follows:
.skip 1
_#_#_#_#_#_#.DMP
.skip 1
The node name should be inserted in place of the _#_#_#_#_#_#.
.skip 2
If you are unsure if a previous dump has been performed a Directory
command should be done as follows:
.skip 1
-Dir #_#_#_#_#_#_.*
.skip 1
The star (*) indicates that you are requesting a list of all files that
relate to the node name specified.
.skip 2
If there is a previous dump file on line the next file should be
named as follows:
.skip 1
_#_#_#_#_#_#.DP1
.SKIP 1
NOTE: If the two files are named the same, the original file will
######be overwritten by the most current dump. 
.page
.center 75
NETWORK CONTROL PROCEDURE
.center 75
STAND-BY NETWORK SUPERVISOR TERMINALS
.skip 4
I. Purpose
This defines the procedure by which the stand-by Supervisor is utilized.
.skip 2
II. Definition
.skip 1
The stand-by Supervisor is a terminal located within Network Control.
The terminal will be logged into the back-up Supervisor via
PROBE. One terminal will monitor the active Supervisor, the other terminal
will be logged into the other Supervisor in a 'ready' state.
.skip 2
III. Procedure
.skip 1
The stand-by monitor terminal should be the first item checked at
the beginning of each shift turnover. The terminal should be logged into
the Kernal host of the back up Supervisor. The 'Drowsiness Factor'
(DF) and the state of the standy-Supervisor should be verified.
The DF should be zero (0), and the state should be 'sleeping'.
Should the state of the stand-by Supervisor be anything but sleeping,
a Network Control Incident ticket should be opened. The new shift
personnel is responsible for checking with the previous shift for
verification of status on the state of the back up Supervisor. 
.skip 2
A 'Log S' command should be issued in PROBE to the  sleeping Supervisor.
This will provide a log of all activity (in seconds) that occurs on
the active Supervisor. It will also provide the time which the sleeping
Supervisor went to sleep, whether by command or otherwise. The logger
should be set to run on hardcopy. This is not needed for the active 
Supervisor. The purpose of the hardcopy is to provide a record of
takeover should the active Supervisor fail, and the stand-by Supervisor
automatically assume control of the network.
.skip 2
If there is a problem with the terminal used for accessing the stand-by
Supervisor another terminal within Network Control should be
designated as a 'back-up' terminal until the primary terminal can be 
repaired.
.skip 2
The stand-by terminal monitoring the 'sleeping' Supervisor should be checked
at least three (3) times during each shift to verify it's operation.
.skip 2
Problems with the stand-by Supervisor or monitoring terminal should be
immediately reported to the proper people for repair. 
.page
.center 75
NETWORK CONTROL PROCEDURE
.center 75
PORT SPEWING CHARACTERS
.skip 4
I. Purpose
.skip 1
This procedure defines the steps taken when the 'Port Spewing Characters'
message is received.
.skip 2
II. Definition
Port Spewing Characters can be defined as a condition  where an
asynchronous port is in an open condition and continuously floods
the Network Supervisor with characters. If this condition
persists it could possibly cause the active Supervisor to crash.
.skip 2
Should there be a problem with spewing characters the message will
print on the PROBE logger in the following format:
.skip 1
Node #, Port # (in decimal), SPEWING CHARACTERS
.skip 1
In the event that this problem should occur the following recovery procedures
should be followed:
.skip 1
.fill
.LEFT MARGIN 15
.justify
.INDENT -4
1.  Do a retake of the node that is 'Spewing Characters'. This will
force the active Supervisor to take 'another look' at node that is
having problems and possibly reset the port that is in question.
.skip 1
.INDENT -4
2.  In the event that a retake is unsuccessful, notify the appropriate 
field engineering group so that they can 'busy out' the problem port.    
.skip 1
.INDENT -4
3.  In the event that a field engineer is unavailable and the node is in
a remote location, a DLOAD and RELOAD should be attempted.
.skip 1
.INDENT -4
4.  If a RELOAD is not effective DLOAD the node and leave it down until
maintenance can go to the site.
.LEFT MARGIN 10
.page
.center 75
NETWORK CONTROL PROCEDURE
.center 75
NETWORK SUPERVISOR MOVES
.skip 4
I. Purpose
This procedure will describe procedures for moving the Network
Supervisor. It will detail scheduled and unscheduled moves.
.skip 2
II. Scheduled Moves
.skip 1
.LEFT MARGIN 10
.FILL
.JUSTIFY
A scheduled move is defined as an active Supervisor being 'put to sleep'
at a scheduled time, and access to the network being denied until another
Network Supervisor is awakened and has control of seventy-five percent
(75%) of the nodes in the network. Seventy-five percent of the
network will be based on the last count of nodes that the previous
Supervisor had control of.
.skip 2
Prior to the actual move, a copy of the ALL NODES list (AN) and the
SHUT TABLE (LSHUT) should be obtained via PROBE. This will give the
Network Controller a current list of all nodes in the network, as well
as a list of all links that were shut prior to takeover.
.skip 2
A TSLEEP command should be given to the active Supervisor. A prompt for  
a password will then appear. The password should be entered, but
the Network Controller SHOULD NOT enter a carriage return <CR> at this
time.
.skip 2
On the sleeping Supervisor a TWAKE command should be entered.
A password prompt will then appear. The password should be entered,
but the carriage return <CR> key SHOULD NOT be depressed.
.skip 2
The Supervisors are now prepared for the move. The Controller should
depress the <CR> on the active Supervisor. The actual time that the 
Supervisor was put to sleep should appear on the screen. The Controller
should wait ten (10) seconds, and then depress the <CR> on the
sleeping Supervisor that is to take over the Network. The Controller 
will get a print out of the actual time that the backup Supervisor
took control of the network.
.skip 2
The Supervisor will takeover all Tymnet II nodes first. The takeover is
complete when the Supervisor has control of the Tymnet I nodes in its
domain, and no nodes are in TAKEOVER FAILURE.
.skip 1
.nofill
.nojustify
** Note: Takeover failure occurs when a node can not achieve
#########all phases of takeover. Tymnet I has four phases
#########(states 0-3), and Tymnet II has only one (state 0).
.fill
.justify
.skip 1
When a node goes into Takeover Failure a retake of the upstream neighbor
generally resolves the problem. In the event that this does not resolve
the problem field engineering should be notified.
.skip 2
When a takeover is successfully accomplished Tymnet performs the
following administrative functions:
.fill
.justify
.LEFT MARGIN 15
.skip 1
.INDENT -4
1. The Network Controller performs a last minute (LSTMIN) command in
PROBE on the Supervisor that has just been put to sleep. This provides
the total number of logins that have taken place since that Supervisor
has had control of the network.
.skip 1
.INDENT -4
2.The version of code that is running on the active Supervisor, PROBE
and the l host is recorded.
.skip 1
.INDENT -4
3. The Network Controller does an ALL NODES (AN) command in PROBE and
compares it to the ALL NODES list that was taken prior to the 
Supervisor move. 
.skip 1
.INDENT -4
4. A Network Incident report is written every time there is a Supervisor
move.
.skip 1
.INDENT -4
5. An Ontyme is sent detailing the Supervisor move. 
.LEFT MARGIN 10
.page
