NETWORK CONTROL PROCEDURE
.center 75
24 HOUR NODE REPORT
.center 75
(Nodes Out for Four or More Consecutive Hours)
.skip 4
I. Purpose
.skip 1
This procedure defines the method and format used for
generating the 24 Hour Node Report.
.skip 2
II. Definition
.skip 1
This report lists all nodes which have been down for four (4)
or more consecutive hours. It also provides the recipient with
the total down time as well as the current status of the outage.
.skip 2
III. Procedure
.skip 1
The Network Controller gathers all ticket information for nodes that have
been out of the network for four or more hours. This information
is divided into types of problems, as well as the region that the problem
is in. The following information is included for each outage:
.skip 1
.fill
.justify
.LEFT MARGIN 15
.INDENT -4
1. The date/time the outage occurred
.skip 1
.INDENT -4
2. All pertinent information about the outage in date/time order and
in summary format
.skip 1
.INDENT -4
3. The name of the group that is currently working on the problem
.skip 2
.fill
.justify
.LEFT MARGIN 10
Once the report has been completed it is sent to a predetermined 
distribution list via Ontyme.
.page
.center 75
NETWORK CONTROL PROCEDURE
.center 75
UTILITY PROGRAMS
.center 75 
(TMCS, XRAY and PROBE)
.skip 4
I. Purpose
.skip 1
This procedure defines the process by which TMCS, XRAY and PROBE
are used by the Network Control. A detailed description of these
utilities can be found in the appropriate manuals
.skip 2
II. Definition
.skip 1
PROBE is a utility package that resides on all Network Supervisors.
PROBE allows the Network Controller to query all network nodes, lines
and host interfaces that the Supervisor currently has control of.
PROBE also allows for some Supervisor control functions.
.skip 2
TMCS (Tymnet Monitoring and Control System) is an interactive system
which allows multiple users to monitor the current state of
nodes, hosts and lines based on a predetermined user
profile. The user profile identifies the nodes, hosts and lines
which that user may monitor.
.skip 2
XRAY is and interactive monitoring and debugging system that provides
a real-time window into a Tymnet II node. Through XRAY a user can
display information the nodes configuration, performance and history.
XRAY is inherent to Tymnet II node code and is a local diagnostic tool
for each node.
.skip 2
III. Procedures
.skip 2
A. PROBE
.skip 1
Network Control should have a terminal logged into PROBE in each 
Supervisor, whether it is active or sleeping. The PROBE terminals
that are logged into sleeping Supervisors should be given the 
'LOG S' command. This serves two purposes:
.skip 1
.fill
.justify
.LEFT MARGIN 15
.INDENT -4
1. This provides a logger in seconds of all events that occur on
the active Supervisor.
.skip 1
.INDENT -4
2. This will provide the time that the inactive Supervisor went to sleep,
as well as monitor activity should the active Supervisor crash and a
backup Supervisor begin taking over the network.
.skip 2
.LEFT MARGIN 10
Listed below are some of the available uses of PROBE, and a partial
listing of frequently used commands:
.NOFILL
.NOJUSTIFY
.LEFT MARGIN 15
.skip 1
 1. Snapping Nodes, Hosts and Lines
 2. Shutting and Clearing Lines
 3. All Nodes List
 4. Sleeping and Awakening Supervisors
 5. RNODE
 6. SYNPRT
 7. DLOAD
 8. Exception List (EXC)
 9. TSTAT
10. BORI and T2BORI
11. Change Neighbors
12. LSTMIN
13. PERDAT
.fill
.justify
.skip 2
.LEFT MARGIN 10
B. TMCS 
.skip 1
At the beginning of each shift the Network Controllers are required
to insure that the designated terminals are logged into TMCS. The
required programs used within Tymnets Network Control are as follows:
.skip 1
.nofill
.nojustify
PROGRAM                            USE
.skip 1
Host                               Monitor All 24 Hour Hosts
Colornode                          Monitor Public Nodes and Hosts
Colorline                          Monitor Network Lines
Log                                Runs the Network Logger
Display                            Display All Network Outages
Gateway                            Monitor Private Network 
                                   Gateways
.skip 1
.fill
.justify
Regardless of the systems used to run TMCS all databases should be
identical as well as kept current.
.skip 2
C. XRAY
.skip 1
XRAY performs three major local diagnostic functions. They are
as follows:
.skip 1
.fill
.justify
.left margin 15
.indent -4
1. Display information about the nodes configuration, performance and 
history
.skip 1
.indent -4
2. Monitor the status of a node's links, trace activity and isolate
problems in the node.
.skip 1
.indent -4
3. XRAY is a debugging tool for programmers which can use it to diagnose
node code and network bugs.
.skip 2
.left margin 10
Network Control uses what is known as 'REMOTE XRAY'. Access is gained
by remotely logging into the Kernal host of a node which is up in the
network. The most common use of XRAY is the Node Descriptor (ND)
command. This lets the Network Controller know more about a node's 
configuration and its current status in one command than they could
using numerous commands in PROBE or TMCS. 
